Theorem 2.1 shows that graph isomorphisms map trajectories to trajectories. Note that, in general, a graph homomorphism does not map trajectories to trajectories. For example, consider (2) on a connected graph G with more than one vertex, let v be a vertex and H be the graph with one vertex v and no edges. Then v has trivial dynamics in H and non-trivial dynamics in G. The embedding \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$H\rightarrow G$$\end{document}H→G does not correspond to a map between dynamical systems. In [14] the notion of graph dynamical system is different, but a similar analysis of these functorial aspects appear.

